China’s provision of lethal aid to Russia for use in Ukraine becomes increasingly unlikely given the following facts. For the period 2017 - 2021 : Substantial increases in Russia’s arms exports to China (60 per cent) and Egypt (723 per cent)—the second and third largest recipients of Russian arms respectively—did not offset the overall decrease in its arms exports. In 2017–21 both China and Egypt received air defence systems and combat aircraft from Russia. Data on China 🇨🇳 for the same period indicate : China accounted for 4.6 per cent of total global arms exports. Chinese arms exports decreased by 31 per cent between 2012–16 and 2017–21. A total of 79 per cent of Chinese arms exports went to Asia and Oceania in 2017–21. China delivered major arms to 48 states in 2017–21, but 47 per cent of its arms exports went to just one state, Pakistan, which is China’s closest ally. Pakistan has become increasingly reliant on Chinese arms exports, partly because of the recent deterioration in its relations with other suppliers, most notably the US.

Cooperation on Gray Zone Conflict strategies between China and Russia is well documented. The key conditions required by the IFP requires a direct link for implementation in Ukraine. While US-China relations are at a low ebb, Beijing ( while belligerent in its political dynamics) seek legitimation and improved relations with the US. While covert reciprocity between Russia and China is real, it’s level of cooperation in various domains continue to increase. Given the uncertainties and whether they can conceal this particular dynamic given the durability of US intelligence in monitoring such activity will determine the success or failure of such an event. Beijing, importantly, seeks parity with the US in many domains and carefully seek to minimize risks associated with this type of event. It also seeks to maintain greater parity over Russia relative to the US.
